  "prompt": "Is the Tamil language older than Sanskrit? How old is it when compared to all other languages of the world?",
  "response": "The Tamil language is indeed one of the oldest continuously spoken languages in the world. It has a rich literary tradition that dates back over 2,000 years, with evidence of Tamil inscriptions found from around 500 BCE or earlier. The earliest known Tamil literature is the Sangam literature, which dates from approximately 300 BCE to 300 CE.\n\nSanskrit, on the other hand, also has ancient roots and is considered one of the oldest languages in the world. It has a documented history going back to around 1500 BCE with the Vedic texts.\n\nWhile definitive comparisons in terms of age can be complex, as languages evolve over time, Tamil is often cited as one of the longest continuously spoken classical languages. It is classified under the Dravidian language family, whereas Sanskrit belongs to the Indo-European family.\n\nWhen considering the age of Tamil against all languages globally, it is important to note that many languages have ancient roots as well, including Sumerian, Egyptian, Akkadian, and others. Each language has its own historical context and development timeline. Thus, while Tamil is certainly ancient and holds a special place in linguistic history, it is part of a broader tapestry of ancient languages.",
